PROJECT BEDROCK
Engineering Charter

Version 1.0

Why Bedrock Exists

Throughout my career, I have worked in environments where talented engineers spent too much of their time searching for information instead of solving problems.

I have watched organizations rely on undocumented knowledge, repetitive manual processes, disconnected tools, and legacy workflows that persisted simply because "that's how we've always done it."

Those experiences shaped the way I think about engineering.

I believe technology should remove complexity rather than create it.

I believe automation should eliminate repetitive work whenever practical.

I believe documentation should preserve knowledge so the next engineer starts from a stronger position instead of rebuilding what already existed.

Most importantly, I believe security engineers should spend their time engineering security—not gathering data.

Project Bedrock exists to document that philosophy while continuously improving the systems, ideas, and engineering practices that support it.

This repository is not simply a record of what I have done.

It is the foundation for what I will continue building throughout my career.

Mission

Engineer systems that enable security professionals to spend more time protecting infrastructure and less time managing technology.

Vision

To build intelligent security platforms that transform security operations from fragmented manual work into contextual engineering decisions through automation, system design, and artificial intelligence.

Core Beliefs
Build on Bedrock

Temporary fixes eventually become technical debt.

Strong engineering creates foundations that continue delivering value long after implementation.

Leave Every System Better Than You Found It

Every project should improve the organization beyond the immediate problem being solved.

Engineer Systems, Not Tasks

The objective is not to perform repetitive work more efficiently.

The objective is to engineer repetitive work out of the process entirely.

Question Everything

"Because that's how we've always done it."

is not an engineering justification.

Every process deserves to be evaluated for opportunities to improve security, reduce complexity, and eliminate unnecessary effort.

Context Before Noise

Security teams rarely need more alerts.

They need better context.

Engineering should reduce cognitive load instead of increasing it.

Automation With Purpose

Automation is valuable only when it improves human capability.

The goal is not replacing engineers.

The goal is enabling them to focus on the work only humans can do.

Truth Above Recognition

Engineering is not about personal recognition.

It is about leaving behind systems that continue creating value after the engineer has moved on.

Long-Term Goal

Everything documented in Project Bedrock should ultimately support one outcome:

Give security engineers their time back.

If an engineer spends less time searching for information...

They spend more time reducing risk.

If they spend more time reducing risk...

Organizations become more secure.

That simple idea is the foundation of everything I build.
